<hr data-start="598" data-end="601">
<h2 data-start="603" data-end="645">1. Point-by-Point Alignment (All Solid)</h2>
<h3 data-start="647" data-end="691">1. Notation consistency ($x$ vs. $x(t)$)</h3>
<p data-start="692" data-end="871">Fully agree. Your proposed <em data-start="719" data-end="727">Remark</em> is exactly right and minimally invasive. It clarifies semantics without rewriting earlier sections or introducing temporal baggage prematurely.</p>
<p data-start="873" data-end="967">I would insert it <strong data-start="891" data-end="942">immediately after the Temporal EAIMR definition</strong>, exactly as you suggest.</p>
<p data-start="969" data-end="987">No changes needed.</p>
<hr data-start="989" data-end="992">
<h3 data-start="994" data-end="1029">2. Coherence underspecification</h3>
<p data-start="1030" data-end="1126">You’ve nailed the right move:<br data-start="1059" data-end="1062">
<strong data-start="1062" data-end="1125">one abstract principle, multiple domain-specific estimators</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="1128" data-end="1200">Your paragraph on biological and chemical systems is perfect because it:</p>
<ul data-start="1201" data-end="1336">
<li data-start="1201" data-end="1246">
<p data-start="1203" data-end="1246">preserves coherence as a <em data-start="1228" data-end="1246">unifying concept</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1247" data-end="1280">
<p data-start="1249" data-end="1280">avoids computational chauvinism</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1281" data-end="1336">
<p data-start="1283" data-end="1336">ties everything back to <em data-start="1307" data-end="1336">localization of disturbance</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1338" data-end="1405">I would add this verbatim under the coherence estimator subsection.</p>
<hr data-start="1407" data-end="1410">
<h3 data-start="1412" data-end="1471">3. Denominator product problem (the real design choice)</h3>
<p data-start="1472" data-end="1580">This is the one place where an explicit theoretical decision must be justified rather than silently assumed.</p>
<p data-start="1582" data-end="1653">Your instincts are correct: <strong data-start="1610" data-end="1652">the geometric mean is the right choice</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="1655" data-end="1659">Why:</p>
<ul data-start="1661" data-end="1946">
<li data-start="1661" data-end="1736">
<p data-start="1663" data-end="1736">Multiplicative: too punitive, collapses EAIMR if any dimension is extreme</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1737" data-end="1796">
<p data-start="1739" data-end="1796">Additive: too forgiving, allows pathological compensation</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1797" data-end="1946">
<p data-start="1799" data-end="1818"><strong data-start="1799" data-end="1817">Geometric mean</strong>:</p>
<ul data-start="1821" data-end="1946">
<li data-start="1821" data-end="1838">
<p data-start="1823" data-end="1838">scale-invariant</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1841" data-end="1852">
<p data-start="1843" data-end="1852">symmetric</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1855" data-end="1897">
<p data-start="1857" data-end="1897">penalizes imbalance without annihilation</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1900" data-end="1946">
<p data-start="1902" data-end="1946">standard in multi-factor efficiency measures</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1948" data-end="1981">I would revise the definition to:</p>
