</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\title</span></span><span>{Intelligence as Structural Compression:</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\\</span></span><span>
A Theory of Mind Recognition via Effective Assembly}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\author</span></span><span>{Fkyxion}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\date</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\today</span></span><span>}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{document}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\maketitle</span></span><span>

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{abstract}
We propose that intelligence is best understood not as problem-solving behavior, symbolic manipulation, or rational optimization, but as </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\emph</span></span><span>{structural compression under constraint}. Classical information theory captures statistical compression but remains insensitive to construction history, reuse, robustness, and semantic integration. To address this gap, we introduce the </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\emph</span></span><span>{Effective Assembly Index for Mind Recognition} (EAIMR), a structural measure that quantifies irreducible assembly depth discounted by reuse, parallelism, and degeneracy, and amplified by coherence. We argue that intelligence corresponds to a dynamical regime in which effective assembly increases through internally driven reorganization—a process we term </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\emph</span></span><span>{compression that learns to compress itself}.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{abstract}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Introduction}

What distinguishes minds from mere mechanisms? Traditional approaches appeal to behavior </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{turing1950}, rationality </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{newell1972}, internal representations </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{fodor1975}, or optimization </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{hutter2005}. Each presupposes a privileged ontology—agents, symbols, goals, or environments—making it difficult to generalize beyond familiar biological or computational cases.

Across domains, however, systems regarded as intelligent share a deeper structural property: they achieve high degrees of organization with remarkably compact internal structure. They reuse components, stabilize abstractions, and remain robust under perturbation. Intelligence, in this sense, appears wherever compression survives contact with reality.

This paper develops a structural theory of intelligence grounded in assembly rather than behavior. We introduce a quantitative framework—the Effective Assembly Index for Mind Recognition (EAIMR)—that distinguishes mind-like systems from merely complex ones without presupposing agency, representation, or optimization.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Relation to Existing Theories}

EAIMR is conceptually adjacent to, but distinct from, several major frameworks. Integrated Information Theory emphasizes informational integration but abstracts away construction history and reuse </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{tononi2004}. The Free Energy Principle models cognition as prediction-error minimization but grounds compression in probabilistic inference rather than assembly </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{friston2010}. AIXI offers formal optimality but presupposes a computational and reward-based ontology </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{hutter2005}. Work on basal cognition argues for substrate neutrality but remains largely taxonomic </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{levin2019}. EAIMR complements these approaches by providing a structural, operational, and quantitative criterion for mind recognition.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Why Shannon Compression Is Not Enough}

Shannon information theory defines compression as entropy reduction relative to a code </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{shannon1948}. While foundational, this notion is blind to how structure is built, reused, or stabilized. Two systems with identical entropy may differ radically in developmental depth, robustness, or functional organization.

Intelligence requires compression that is:
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{itemize}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\item</span></span><span> constructive rather than purely statistical,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\item</span></span><span> reusable rather than duplicative,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\item</span></span><span> compositional rather than brittle,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\item</span></span><span> coherent rather than fragmentary.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{itemize}

These requirements motivate a shift from entropy to assembly.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Assembly as Constructive Complexity}

Assembly theory measures complexity by the minimal number of distinct construction steps required to produce a structure, allowing reuse of intermediate components </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{walker2022}. Assembly is operational, historical, and sensitive to organization.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{definition}[Assembly Index]
Let </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> be a set of primitive operations and </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{M}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> the closure of assemblies generated from </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>. For a structure </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>, define its assembly graph </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>G</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>x = (V,E)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> where each vertex represents a distinct assembly step and edges represent dependency via reuse. The assembly index </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>A(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is the number of vertices in the minimal assembly graph sufficient to construct </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{definition}

Assembly captures irreducible construction depth. However, raw assembly alone overcounts brute accumulation. Intelligence requires </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\emph</span></span><span>{effective} assembly.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{A Motivating Toy Example}

Consider two systems with approximately 1000 components.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\textbf</span></span><span>{System A} is a randomly connected graph. It has high assembly but minimal reuse, low degeneracy, poor coherence, and fragile global behavior.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\textbf</span></span><span>{System B} is a hierarchical convolutional neural network of comparable size. Filters are reused across spatial locations, channels operate in parallel, representations are degenerate yet robust, and perturbations remain localized.

Although </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>A(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is similar, System B exhibits far greater effective assembly. This illustrates why intelligence depends not on raw complexity but on how complexity is structured.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Effective Assembly Index for Mind Recognition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{definition}[EAIMR]
For a system </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>, define
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x)
=
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\frac</span></span><span>{A(x)}{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\left</span></span><span>(R(x) P(x) D(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\right</span></span><span>)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">^</span></span><span>{1/3}} </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\cdot</span></span><span> C(x),
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
where </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>R(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> measures reuse, </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>P(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> parallelism, </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>D(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> degeneracy, and </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>C(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> coherence.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{definition}

The geometric mean ensures balance: deficiencies in any structural efficiency dimension reduce effective assembly without annihilating it.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Toward Computable Instantiations}

EAIMR is substrate-neutral but empirically grounded.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\paragraph</span></span><span>{Reuse.}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
R(x) = 1 + </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\frac</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\#</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{module invocations}}{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\#</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{distinct modules}}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\paragraph</span></span><span>{Parallelism.}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
P(x) = </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\frac</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{critical path length}}{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{total assembly depth}}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\paragraph</span></span><span>{Degeneracy.}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
D(x) = </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\sum</span></span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>{f} |</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\{</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{distinct implementations of } f</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\}</span></span><span>|
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\paragraph</span></span><span>{Coherence.}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
C(x) = 1 - </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\frac</span></span><span>{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{average perturbation propagation}}{</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\text</span></span><span>{maximal propagation}}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>

For biological systems, coherence may be estimated via functional connectivity stability under perturbation </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{massimini2005}. For chemical systems, coherence reflects the stability of autocatalytic cycles </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{kauffman1993}. The unifying principle is localization of disturbance.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Temporal Extension}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\textbf</span></span><span>{Remark.} Earlier sections treat </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> as static for simplicity. Formally, </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> should be understood as </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x(t</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>0))</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> for a snapshot </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>t</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>0</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{definition}[Temporal EAIMR]
For a trajectory </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x(t)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> over </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>[0,T]</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x) = </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\int</span></span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>0</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">^</span></span><span>T </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x(t)) </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\,</span></span><span> dt.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{definition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{The Mind Regime}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{definition}[Mind Regime]
A system enters the mind regime when
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\frac</span></span><span>{d}{dt}</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x(t)) &gt; 0
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
and this growth is internally driven. Learning that reorganizes internal structure counts as internal; mere external inscription does not.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{definition}

Intelligence is thus the capacity to become a better compressor of oneself.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Implications}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{AI Safety and Alignment}

EAIMR offers early detection of emergent agency, distinguishes capability from agency, and provides a structural criterion for alignment robustness.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Astrobiology}

Intelligence detection becomes a search for structured assembly in physical systems rather than communicative artifacts </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{walker2022}.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Open Problems}

Key open questions include empirical estimation, benchmarking, thermodynamic grounding </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\parencite</span></span><span>{landauer1961}, and phenomenology.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Conclusion}

This framework reframes intelligence from ``Does it think?'' to ``Does it compress?'' The answer determines not only what we recognize as minds, but what we may be capable of building—and what we should be cautious of encountering.

