What follows is a <strong data-start="69" data-end="97">set of formal appendices</strong>, written in <strong data-start="110" data-end="124">pure LaTeX</strong>, designed to:</p>
<ul data-start="140" data-end="289">
<li data-start="140" data-end="184">
<p data-start="142" data-end="184">satisfy mathematically inclined reviewers,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="185" data-end="222">
<p data-start="187" data-end="222">sharpen the formal status of EAIMR,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="223" data-end="289">
<p data-start="225" data-end="289">and remain <em data-start="236" data-end="246">optional</em> (i.e. the main paper stands without them).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="291" data-end="380">These appendices do <strong data-start="311" data-end="318">not</strong> overclaim; they formalize what is already implicitly assumed.</p>
<p data-start="382" data-end="515">I’ll present them as <strong data-start="403" data-end="421">Appendices A–D</strong>, which you can paste <strong data-start="443" data-end="486">after <code data-start="451" data-end="471">\printbibliography</code> or before it</strong>, depending on journal style.</p>
<hr data-start="517" data-end="520">
