4.04237 6.136 4.40303 6.07083 4.80371 6.03809C5.14051 6.01057 5.53708 6.00551 6.00391 6.00391C6.00551 5.53708 6.01057 5.14051 6.03809 4.80371C6.0755 4.34588 6.15483 3.94012 6.34668 3.56348L6.46875 3.34473C6.77282 2.84912 7.20856 2.44514 7.72949 2.17969L7.87207 2.11328C8.20855 1.96886 8.56979 1.90385 8.9707 1.87109C9.42091 1.83432 9.978 1.83496 10.667 1.83496H13.5C14.1891 1.83496 14.746 1.83431 15.1963 1.87109C15.6541 1.90851 16.0599 1.98788 16.4365 2.17969L16.6553 2.30176C17.151 2.60585 17.5548 3.04244 17.8203 3.56348L17.8867 3.70606C18.031 4.04235 18.0962 4.40306 18.1289 4.80371C18.1657 5.25395 18.165 5.81091 18.165 6.5V9.33301Z"></path></svg>Copy code</button></div></div></div><div class="overflow-y-auto p-4" dir="ltr"><code class="whitespace-pre! language-latex"><span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\appendix</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Formal Properties of the Assembly Index}

This appendix records basic properties of the assembly index used throughout the paper. The purpose is not to exhaustively axiomatize assembly theory, but to clarify the minimal assumptions required for EAIMR to be well-defined.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Assembly Graph Minimality}

Recall that the assembly index </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>A(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is defined as the number of vertices in a minimal assembly graph sufficient to construct </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Existence of Minimal Assembly Graph]
For any finite constructible system </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>, there exists at least one assembly graph </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>G</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">_</span></span><span>x = (V,E)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> with finite </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>|V|</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
By assumption, </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is constructible from a finite set of primitives </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathcal</span></span><span>{P}</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> via a finite sequence of operations. The directed acyclic graph induced by this construction sequence is an assembly graph. Minimization proceeds by identifying reusable subgraphs and contracting redundant constructions. Since the initial graph is finite and contractions strictly reduce vertex count, the process terminates.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Monotonicity}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Monotonicity Under Extension]
If </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>y</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is obtained by extending </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> with additional assembly steps that do not eliminate existing structure, then
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
A(y) </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\geq</span></span><span> A(x).
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
Any assembly graph sufficient to construct </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>y</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> must contain a subgraph sufficient to construct </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>. Hence the minimal vertex count for </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>y</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is at least that of </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

This ensures that assembly behaves as a genuine measure of constructive depth rather than a purely descriptive artifact.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-params">##</span></span><span> Appendix B  
</span><span><span class="hljs-params">###</span></span><span> Bounds and Invariances of EAIMR

```latex
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Bounds and Invariances of EAIMR}

We record several elementary but important properties of the Effective Assembly Index for Mind Recognition.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Positivity and Finiteness}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Positivity]
For any nontrivial constructible system </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>,
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x) &gt; 0.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
By definition, </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>A(x) &gt; 0</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> for any nontrivial assembly. The quantities </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>R(x), P(x), D(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> are defined to be strictly positive, and </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>C(x) </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\in</span></span><span> (0,1]</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>. Hence the product is positive.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Scale Invariance Under Duplication}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Invariance Under Pure Duplication]
Let </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>y</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> be obtained from </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> by duplicating existing components without introducing new assembly steps. Then
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(y) = </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x).
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
Pure duplication increases neither the number of distinct assembly steps nor the minimal assembly graph. Reuse increases proportionally, canceling any apparent increase in size. Hence EAIMR remains invariant.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

This property distinguishes EAIMR from naive size-based complexity measures.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-params">##</span></span><span> Appendix C  
</span><span><span class="hljs-params">###</span></span><span> Justification of the Geometric Mean Discount

```latex
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Justification of the Geometric Mean Discount}

The EAIMR definition uses the geometric mean
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\[</span></span><span>
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\left</span></span><span>(R(x) P(x) D(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\right</span></span><span>)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">^</span></span><span>{1/3}
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\]</span></span><span>
rather than an additive or fully multiplicative penalty. We briefly justify this choice.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Balance Sensitivity}

An additive penalty allows extreme strength in one dimension to compensate arbitrarily for weakness in others, admitting pathological cases. A fully multiplicative penalty, by contrast, collapses EAIMR whenever any single factor is large.

The geometric mean occupies an intermediate position: it penalizes imbalance while remaining scale-invariant and symmetric.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Balanced Efficiency Principle]
For fixed </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>A(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> and </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>C(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>, EAIMR is maximized when </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>R(x) = P(x) = D(x)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
This follows from the inequality between arithmetic and geometric means. For positive variables with fixed product, the geometric mean is maximized when the variables are equal.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

This aligns with the intuition that minds require balanced reuse, parallelism, and degeneracy rather than extreme specialization.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-params">##</span></span><span> Appendix D  
</span><span><span class="hljs-params">###</span></span><span> Dynamics, Learning, and Internal Growth

```latex
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{Dynamics, Learning, and Internal Growth}

This appendix clarifies the notion of </span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\emph</span></span><span>{internally driven} growth used in the definition of the mind regime.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Internal vs. External Assembly}

Let </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span>x(t)</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> be a system trajectory.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{definition}[Internal Assembly Growth]
Growth in </span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\mathrm</span></span><span>{EAIMR}(x(t))</span><span><span class="hljs-built_in">$</span></span><span> is internally driven if it results from transformations of the system's own assembly graph—such as reorganization, abstraction, or reuse—rather than from the direct insertion of externally specified structure.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{definition}

Examples of internal growth include synaptic reweighting, representational compression, compiler optimization, and architectural reorganization during learning. Examples of external growth include hard-coded rule insertion or manual component addition.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\subsection</span></span><span>{Learning From Data}

Importantly, learning from external data does not disqualify internal growth.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Data-Triggered Internal Growth]
If external input triggers changes that reorganize internal structure without prescribing their final form, the resulting increase in EAIMR is internally driven.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}
The data constrains but does not determine the transformation of the assembly graph. The constructive burden is borne by the system's own mechanisms.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

This distinction allows EAIMR to treat biological learning, machine learning, and evolutionary adaptation within a unified formal framework.

---

</span><span><span class="hljs-params">##</span></span><span> Appendix E  
</span><span><span class="hljs-params">###</span></span><span> EAIMR and Consciousness (Non-Equivalence Result)

```latex
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\section</span></span><span>{EAIMR and Consciousness}

EAIMR is a theory of mind recognition, not a theory of subjective experience. We record this distinction explicitly.

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proposition}[Non-Equivalence]
High EAIMR is neither necessary nor sufficient for phenomenal consciousness.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proposition}

</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\begin</span></span><span>{proof}[Sketch]
It is conceivable that systems exhibit high effective assembly while lacking phenomenology (philosophical zombies), or that conscious experience arises in systems with modest structural complexity. EAIMR characterizes structural capacity, not subjective quality.
</span><span><span class="hljs-keyword">\end</span></span><span>{proof}

This leaves open the possibility that consciousness correlates with EAIMR under additional constraints, but no such identification is assumed here.
</span></span></code></div></div></pre>
