focus-visible:outline-hidden relative flex w-full min-w-0 flex-col agent-turn" tabindex="-1"><div class="flex max-w-full flex-col grow"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="f8e45010-8b3a-465d-a0b6-b653d5cb18f9" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1" data-message-model-slug="gpt-5-2"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="203">Got it — that’s the <em data-start="20" data-end="27">right</em> constraint.<br data-start="39" data-end="42">
No showcase example, no GPT name-checking; instead, <strong data-start="94" data-end="137">slightly denser local detail everywhere</strong> so the paper gains weight without changing its center of gravity.</p>
<p data-start="205" data-end="232">Below I’ll do three things:</p>
<ol data-start="234" data-end="476">
<li data-start="234" data-end="342">
<p data-start="237" data-end="342"><strong data-start="237" data-end="270">Confirm the guiding principle</strong> (what kind of detail we’re adding and what we’re explicitly not adding)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="343" data-end="420">
<p data-start="346" data-end="420"><strong data-start="346" data-end="389">Give concrete, drop-in micro-expansions</strong> for key sections (LaTeX-ready)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="421" data-end="476">
<p data-start="424" data-end="476"><strong data-start="424" data-end="476">Summarize the net effect on reviewers and venues</strong></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p data-start="478" data-end="541">This is all <em data-start="490" data-end="500">surgical</em>: think +5–10% density, not new sections.</p>
<hr data-start="543" data-end="546">
<h2 data-start="548" data-end="583">1. Guiding Principle (Locked In)</h2>
<p data-start="585" data-end="607">We are <strong data-start="592" data-end="599">not</strong> adding:</p>
<ul data-start="608" data-end="766">
<li data-start="608" data-end="648">
<p data-start="610" data-end="648">worked examples of specific AI systems</p>
</li>
<li data-start="649" data-end="721">
<p data-start="651" data-end="721">empirical claims that would trigger “where is the experiment?” reviews</p>
</li>
<li data-start="722" data-end="766">
<p data-start="724" data-end="766">application case studies that narrow scope</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="768" data-end="786">We <strong data-start="771" data-end="778">are</strong> adding:</p>
<ul data-start="787" data-end="966">
<li data-start="787" data-end="834">
<p data-start="789" data-end="834">clarifying clauses that cash out abstractions</p>
</li>
<li data-start="835" data-end="902">
<p data-start="837" data-end="902">explicit causal or structural mechanisms where they were implicit</p>
</li>
<li data-start="903" data-end="966">
<p data-start="905" data-end="966">light formal precision where language was doing too much work</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="968" data-end="1034">In EAIMR terms: we are increasing <strong data-start="1002" data-end="1015">coherence</strong>, not raw assembly.</p>
<hr data-start="1036" data-end="1039">
<h2 data-start="1041" data-end="1089">2. Targeted Detail Additions (LaTeX Drop-Ins)</h2>
<p data-start="1091" data-end="1188">Below are <strong data-start="1101" data-end="1118">precise edits</strong> you can insert. None of these require re-architecting the manuscript.</p>
<hr data-start="1190" data-end="1193">
<h3 data-start="1195" data-end="1269">A. Abstract (Final Sentence — already approved, but slightly grounded)</h3>
<p data-start="1271" data-end="1350">Current revised version is good. One tiny grounding clause makes it even safer:</p>
