3.67069 11.4985 3 10.827 3 9.99963C3.00018 9.17239 3.6708 8.50176 4.49805 8.50159Z"></path><path d="M10.0003 8.50159C10.8276 8.50176 11.4982 9.17239 11.4984 9.99963C11.4984 10.827 10.8277 11.4985 10.0003 11.4987C9.17283 11.4987 8.50131 10.8271 8.50131 9.99963C8.50149 9.17228 9.17294 8.50159 10.0003 8.50159Z"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></article><article class="text-token-text-primary w-full focus:outline-none [--shadow-height:45px] has-data-writing-block:pointer-events-none has-data-writing-block:-mt-(--shadow-height) has-data-writing-block:pt-(--shadow-height) [&amp;:has([data-writing-block])&gt;*]:pointer-events-auto scroll-mt-(--header-height)" tabindex="-1" dir="auto" data-turn-id="bbb21b23-4510-4bb1-8cac-d4bbb080681c" data-testid="conversation-turn-53" data-scroll-anchor="false" data-turn="user"><h5 class="sr-only">You said:</h5><div class="text-base my-auto mx-auto pt-12 [--thread-content-margin:--spacing(4)] @w-sm/main:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(6)] @w-lg/main:[--thread-content-margin:--spacing(16)] px-(--thread-content-margin)"><div class="[--thread-content-max-width:40rem] @w-lg/main:[--thread-content-max-width:48rem] mx-auto max-w-(--thread-content-max-width) flex-1 group/turn-messages focus-visible:outline-hidden relative flex w-full min-w-0 flex-col" tabindex="-1"><div class="flex max-w-full flex-col grow"><div data-message-author-role="user" data-message-id="bbb21b23-4510-4bb1-8cac-d4bbb080681c" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden items-end rtl:items-start"><div class="user-message-bubble-color corner-superellipse/1.1 relative rounded-[18px] px-4 py-1.5 data-[multiline]:py-3 max-w-[var(--user-chat-width,70%)]" data-multiline=""><div class="whitespace-pre-wrap">Is there a way we can integrate this into the framework!? Professor Yi Ma's talk, "The Mathematical Foundations of Intelligence," outlines his framework for a mathematical theory of intelligence, primarily focusing on its foundational principles and the distinction between current AI practices and true understanding.
Here is a summary of the key concepts discussed:
1. The Mathematical Theory of Intelligence
Professor Ma's recently published book, Learning Deep Representations of Data Distributions, proposes a mathematical theory of intelligence built on two core principles:
 * Parsimony (Compression): This is the process of discovering what is predictable about the world by finding the most simple, low-dimensional representation of the data. It involves processes like compression, denoising, and dimension reduction, seeking to explain things "as simple as possible".
 * Self-Consistency (Consistency): This ensures that the memory, or "world model," is consistent and accurate enough to be able to "recreate [and] simulate the world just right". It means the model should not be any simpler than necessary, as that would lose predictivity.
He asserts that these two principles govern how memory is formed and works at the level of intelligence common to animals and humans, helping with survival by using memory to predict and react to the world.
2. Stages and Levels of Intelligence
Professor Ma identifies four stages of intelligence or knowledge accumulation:
 * Phylogenetic Accumulation (Evolution): Knowledge gained through evolution and encoded in DNA, which he describes as a very brutal and unpredictable compression process (natural selection).
 * Ontogenetic Accumulation (Individual Learning): An individual's ability, developed through the brain and neural systems, to learn from observations and build memories of the world, rather than just inheriting knowledge.
 * Social Accumulation: The knowledge shared and recorded in languages and texts within a human society.
 * Science and Abstraction: The transition, which he calls a "phase transition," from acquiring empirical knowledge (compression) to developing abstract, formalized, and deductive knowledge, such as mathematics and physics.
3. The Distinction Between Memorization/Compression and Understanding/Abstraction
A core theme of the talk is the fundamental difference between compression/memorization and abstraction/understanding.
 * Current AI (LLMs): Professor Ma argues that current large language models (LLMs) are primarily memorizing the statistical structures of text using a mechanism similar to how we acquire empirical knowledge (compression). He points out that natural language itself is already a result of compression and abstraction of knowledge we learned through our physical senses and world models. Therefore, LLMs are compressing an already compressed signal.
 * The Open Question: This leads to the big open problems for the future:
   * What is the difference between compression and abstraction?
   * What is the difference between memorization and understanding?
He suggests that the level of intelligence where true scientific discovery and rigorous deductive logic (abstraction) are possible is what the pioneers of the field in 1956 truly meant by "true artificial intelligence".
4. Connection to Information Theory and Cybernetics
 * Maximum Rate Coding Reduction: The discussion on the low-dimensional structure of data led him to a more generalized notion of data "volume" that can be measured using entropy. His work on maximum rate coding reduction aims to not only reduce the coding rate to find the data distribution but also to transform the data into a new, structured, and organized representation that maximizes this reduction, facilitating efficient access to memory.
 * Cybernetics: He cites Norbert Wiener's work on cybernetics, noting that it was focused on the animal/common human level of intelligence (how the brain works). Wiener's work characterized the necessary characteristics for an intelligent system, including the need for information theory, feedback control (to correct error), and game theory (for decision-making). He notes that this focus on a closed-loop learning mechanism (constant prediction and correction) is only possible if the world's distribution is low-dimensional enough.
