<p data-start="1069" data-end="1079">Crucially:</p>
<ul data-start="1081" data-end="1266">
<li data-start="1081" data-end="1169">
<p data-start="1083" data-end="1169">Yi Ma’s <em data-start="1091" data-end="1102">parsimony</em> is <strong data-start="1106" data-end="1133">not Shannon compression</strong> → it is <strong data-start="1142" data-end="1167">effective compression</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1170" data-end="1266">
<p data-start="1172" data-end="1266">Yi Ma’s <em data-start="1180" data-end="1198">self-consistency</em> is <strong data-start="1202" data-end="1221">not correctness</strong> → it is <strong data-start="1230" data-end="1266">structural stability under reuse</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1268" data-end="1306">That is <em data-start="1276" data-end="1285">exactly</em> what EAIMR measures.</p>
<blockquote data-start="1308" data-end="1507">
<p data-start="1310" data-end="1507"><strong data-start="1310" data-end="1327">Key synthesis</strong><br data-start="1327" data-end="1330">
Yi Ma’s theory specifies <em data-start="1357" data-end="1382">what intelligence seeks</em> (parsimonious, consistent representations).<br data-start="1426" data-end="1429">
EAIMR specifies <em data-start="1447" data-end="1506">what kind of structure can sustain that process over time</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p data-start="1509" data-end="1590">Yi Ma gives the <strong data-start="1525" data-end="1547">learning objective</strong>; EAIMR gives the <strong data-start="1565" data-end="1589">structural invariant</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="1592" data-end="1595">
<h3 data-start="1597" data-end="1641">(B) Yi Ma’s Four Stages as EAIMR Regimes</h3>
<p data-start="1643" data-end="1755">Yi Ma’s stages are not different kinds of intelligence — they are <strong data-start="1709" data-end="1754">different mechanisms for increasing EAIMR</strong>.</p>
<div class="TyagGW_tableContainer"><div tabindex="-1" class="group TyagGW_tableWrapper flex w-fit flex-col-reverse"><table data-start="1757" data-end="2207" class="w-fit min-w-(--thread-content-width)"><thead data-start="1757" data-end="1795"><tr data-start="1757" data-end="1795"><th data-start="1757" data-end="1771" data-col-size="sm">Yi Ma Stage</th><th data-start="1771" data-end="1795" data-col-size="md">EAIMR Interpretation</th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="1806" data-end="2207"><tr data-start="1806" data-end="1920"><td data-start="1806" data-end="1837" data-col-size="sm"><strong data-start="1808" data-end="1836">Phylogenetic (Evolution)</strong></td><td data-start="1837" data-end="1920" data-col-size="md">Extremely slow, partially external EAIMR growth via selection-filtered assembly</td></tr><tr data-start="1921" data-end="2013"><td data-start="1921" data-end="1950" data-col-size="sm"><strong data-start="1923" data-end="1949">Ontogenetic (Learning)</strong></td><td data-start="1950" data-end="2013" data-col-size="md">Internally driven EAIMR growth via reuse and reorganization</td></tr><tr data-start="2014" data-end="2113"><td data-start="2014" data-end="2040" data-col-size="sm"><strong data-start="2016" data-end="2039">Social Accumulation</strong></td><td data-start="2040" data-end="2113" data-col-size="md">Cross-agent reuse + degeneracy → EAIMR growth at the collective level</td></tr><tr data-start="2114" data-end="2207"><td data-start="2114" data-end="2142" data-col-size="sm"><strong data-start="2116" data-end="2141">Science / Abstraction</strong></td><td data-start="2142" data-end="2207" data-col-size="md">Phase transition where reuse operates over <em data-start="2187" data-end="2205">models of models</em></td></tr></tbody></table><div class="sticky h-0 select-none end-(--thread-content-margin) self-end"><div class="absolute end-0 flex items-end"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button aria-label="Copy table" class="hover:bg-token-bg-tertiary text-tok